column3: The third wave was an experiment in 1967 that was developed in Palo Alto, California by Ron Jones. He conducted this experiment because he was unable to explain to his students how people throughout history followed the crowed when terrible things were happening. He developed the experiment by enforcing strict classroom disipline. Some of the rules were the students had to stand up to ask or answer questions and they had to do it in three words or fewer, and were required to begin each remark with "Mr. Jones". On the fourth day of the experiment Mr. Jones had to end the experiment because he felt that it was slipping out of control. The students were very   involved with the experiment and demostrated how people create a sense of  superiority over others, and how it can lead to people doing horrible things in the name of the state's honor.
column4: The third wave experiment was a study conducted in 1967 by Ron Jones in Palo Alto, California. Jones aimed to investigate the phenomenon of people following the crowed when terrible events were occurring. He implemented strict classroom discipline to ensure order and minimize distractions. Furthermore, Jones set specific guidelines for student behavior, emphasizing brevity and clarity in communication. However, on the fourth day of the experiment, Jones had to abruptly terminate the study due to escalating uncontrollable behavior demonstrated by the students. Despite the challenging circumstances, the experiment revealed the humans' desire for social superiority and emphasized the potential for individuals to engage in harmful behaviors for the sake of their nation's honor.

column3: Aristotle describes the ideal tragedy as a story in which a mundane character who is neither righteous nor evil  and experieneces  an unfortunate event caused by their own misjudgement, in essence Aristotle writes that the perfect tragedy should elicite both pity and fear.  Aristotle writes, "there remains, then, the character between these two extremes — that of a man who is not eminently good and just, yet whose misfortune is brought about not by vice or depravity, but by some error of judgement or frailty" (2) explaining how when writing a tragedy one must follow a  balanced character who causes their own downfall through a relatable means. Additionally the ideal tragedy must "imitate actions which excite pity and fear" (2) so that the viewer both sympathizes with the character and fears that they too could suffer the same fate.
column4: Aristotle's ideal tragedy is a story about a character who falls between virtue and villainy, and experiences an unfortunate event that is the result of their own misjudgment. As a result, the tragedy should elicit both pity and fear in the audience.   To write an effective tragedy, the author must create a character that the audience can relate to and care about. The tragedy should also show how the character's misfortune is caused by an error of judgment or frailty. Additionally, the tragedy must use actions that evoke both pity and fear in order to create an emotional connection with the audience.

column4: The social hierarchy in ancient Egypt was divided into various social classes that played important roles in society. The pharaoh was revered as a god and held the highest position in society. Following the pharaoh were priests, nobles, and supervisors. The middle class was composed of physicians, craftsmen, women, traders, and artisans. The lowest social class was comprised of slaves and farmers, facing harsh living conditions. They played a vital role in maintaining order and maintaining the government.  The social classes were interconnected and had varying levels of influence within society. The high class, led by the pharaoh, held the ultimate power and made critical decisions that impacted the entire society. Scribes were crucial to maintaining order by recording and documenting important events. The middle class participated in trade and commerce, enriching the society with various products and services. A significant portion of the middle class were skilled artisans, contributing to the economy. Some individuals from the middle class even held positions of leadership in the government.

column3: The Third Wave started out as an innocent and harmless experiment but eventually got worse and worse and started to resemble a Nazi regime.  At first Jones created strict classroom rules, but then he made up the Nazi regime-resembelling salute that all the members had to do when they passed each other. More and more students started joining even though it was supposed to stay within one class and only last a day, and it started to get out of hand. Students would report other students who were not following rules and they would initiate new members on the daily. Jones decided to end the experiment because "the students became increasingly involved in the project and their discipline and loyalty to the project was so outstanding that Jones felt it was slipping out of control". He knew it was best for him and the well being of the students if he terminated the Third Wave.
column4: The Third Wave started innocently enough, but as the days went on, it took a turn for the worse. Jones instituted strict classroom rules, creating a semblance of a Nazi regime. Initially, he enforced them as usual; however, students gradually began to join the project, even though it was intended to be a one-day experiment. As the number of participants grew, the project escalated out of control. Students complained about each other's behavior and initiated new members each day, causing Jones to terminate the Third Wave after realizing the project's growing influence on the students' behavior and dedication.

column3: One element of an ideal tradegy, as described by Aristole, is that it should be arranged in a complex plan. This means that it should not be organized in a simple way. A second element of an ideal tradegy is that it should imitate actions in which excite pity and fear. This should be the main element of an ideal tragedy. column4: An ideal tragedy should be complex in its structure. It should not be presented in a straightforward manner. The main emphasis should be on creating a sense of pity and fear in the audience. A lower echelon included powerful nobility and priests with restricted participation in government positions. At the base of the societal pyramid were slaves and farmers, their lives marked by hardship and dependence on the government for their survival.
